== Description ==
Measuring around {{convert|14|cm|in|abbr=on|frac=2}} in length, the sociable weaver has a black chin, black, barred flanks, and a scalloped back.<ref name="Sinclair">{{cite book|last= Sinclair|first= Ian|title= Field Guide to Birds of Southern Africa|publisher= Struik|location= Cape Town, RSA|year= 1993|orig-date= 1984|page= 02|isbn= 978-0-86977-435-9}}</ref> It typically weighs {{convert|26|-|32|g|oz|abbr=on|frac=16}}, and sexes are indistinguishable.<ref name=covas /> Tail Length around {{convert|42|-|48|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sociable Weaver (Philetairus socius) Fact Sheet |url=https://ielc.libguides.com/sdzg/factsheets/sociableweaver/characteristics |website=ielc.libguides.com/}}</ref>

== Distribution and habitat ==
The species ranges across northwestern South Africa and southwest Botswana, and extending northwards across Namibia.<ref name=Sinclair/> It is strongly associated with the arid savannas characteristic of the southern Kalahari region.<ref name=covas /> The presence of stiff grasses such as ''[[Stipagrostis ciliata]]'' (syn. ''Aristida ciliata'') – an important nesting material – is an important determinant of its distribution.<ref name=mendelsohn /> The taller grasses and the fire-prone nature of the Northern and Central Kalahari regions may be a factor for the absence of the bird in those regions.<ref name=mendelsohn /> The area is semiarid with low and unpredictable rainfall occurring mostly in the summer. The population has not been quantified, but the birds are described as "common to abundant".<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" />

== Behaviour and ecology ==
=== Breeding ===
In the southern range of the weaver's habitat, breeding may occur any time of the year and is closely linked to rainfall. In the northern range, a discrete breeding season between December and August has been noted.<ref name=mendelsohn /> They may skip breeding during years when rainfall is low and a substantial number (sometimes over half) of birds in the colony may never breed in a given season.<ref name=covas /> Under typical conditions, weavers raise up to four broods per breeding cycle. Sociable weavers are known to assist in the care of younger siblings and unrelated hatchlings, and nearly all pairs are assisted by helpers.<ref name=covas /> A mating pair has been recorded as producing nine [[offspring|brood]]s in a single season in response to repeated predation of its young. Unlike northern temperate passerine birds, which commence breeding within the first year of life, sociable weavers exhibit delayed-onset breeding, at sometimes up to two years of age.<ref name=covas />

=== Nesting ===
{{Multiimage
| image1            = Webervogelnst Auoblodge.JPG
| caption1          = The [[Bird colony|nesting colonies]] of the sociable weaver are amongst the largest bird-created structures.
| image2            = Camel Thorn (Vachellia erioloba) with Sociable Weavers (Philetairus socius) collective nests ... (50981196923).jpg
| caption2          = [[Vachellia erioloba|Camel thorn]] with Sociable weavers' nests.
| direction         = vertical
}}
Sociable weavers construct permanent nests on trees and other tall objects. These nests are amongst the largest built by any bird, and are large enough to house over 100 pairs of birds,<ref name="nest 1">{{cite journal|last=White|first=Fred |author2=Bartholomew, Gerorge |author3=Thomas Howell|year=1975|title=The thermal significance of the nest of the sociable weaver ''Philetairus socius'': winter observations|journal=Ibis|volume=117|issue=2|pages=171–179 | doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.1975.tb04205.x}}</ref> containing several generations at a time. The nests are highly structured and provide birds with a more advantageous temperature relative to the outside. The central chambers retain heat and are used for nighttime roosting. The outer rooms are used for daytime shade, inside temperatures in occupied chambers have been found to vary over a range of only 7–8 °C (12.6–14.4 °F) while outside temperatures varied from 16-33.5 °C (60.8-92.3 °F).<ref name="bartholomew">{{cite journal|last=Bartholomew|first=George A|author2=Fred N White |author3=Thomas R Howell |title=The thermal significance of the nest of the sociable weaver ''Philetairus socius'': summer observations |journal=Ibis|date=July 1976|volume=118|issue=6|pages=402–411|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1976.tb02027.x}}</ref>

The nests consist of separate chambers, each of which is occupied by a pair (sometimes with offspring) and used to roost and breed. Nests are built around large and sturdy structures such as acacia trees or sometimes even telephone poles. The trees generally used for nest-building are ''[[Acacia erioloba]]'', ''[[Boscia albitrunca]]'', and ''[[Aloidendron dichotomum]]''. The birds at [[Etosha National Park]] also use ''[[Colophospermum mopane]]'' trees for nesting.<ref name="mendelsohn" /> Large nesting colonies can be active across many generations, sometimes over 199 years.<ref name="covas" /><ref name="Sandiego">{{cite web|title= Birds: Sociable Weavers|url= https://www.sandiegozoo.org/animalbytes/t-sociable_weavers.html|work= San Diego Zoo: Animals and plants|publisher= Zoological society of San Diego|access-date= 18 January 2011|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101223082506/http://sandiegozoo.org/animalbytes/t-sociable_weavers.html|archive-date= 2010-12-23}}</ref> The nest appears like a large haystack in the tree. If seen from below, entrances into the chambers may be seen, giving a honeycomb appearance. The entrances may be about {{convert|3|in|abbr=on}} wide and can be up to {{convert|10|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name="Sandiego" /> Sharp sticks may be placed to deter predators from entering.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}

Sociable weaver nests form a habitat that is occupied by animals of many different taxa, including several other bird species, which use the nest in different ways, such as for breeding (as with the [[Red-headed finch|paradise finch]] and [[rosy-faced lovebird]]), roosting (as with the [[familiar chat]] and [[ashy tit]]), or as a platform for the nests of larger birds (such as owls, vultures, or falcons).<ref name="mendelsohn" /><ref name="Sandiego" /> Although most birds use sociable weaver nests commensally, cases of predation upon nestlings and animosity with the weavers has been reported of the [[Polihierax semitorquatus|pygmy falcon]] in some sites in [[Kimberley, Northern Cape|Kimberley]].<ref name="covas2">{{cite journal|last= Covas|first= Rita|author2= Otto Huyser|author3= Claire Doutrelant|title= Pygmy Falcon predation of nestlings of their obligate host, the Sociable Weaver|journal= Ostrich: Journal of African Ornithology|year= 2004|volume= 75|issue= 4|pages= 325–326|url= http://www.cefe.cnrs.fr/esp/publis/RC/RC2004_CovasEtal%20Pigmy%20Falcon%20Ostrich04.pdf|access-date= 18 January 2011|doi= 10.2989/00306520409485463|bibcode= 2004Ostri..75..325C|s2cid= 85568509|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110718164918/http://www.cefe.cnrs.fr/esp/publis/RC/RC2004_CovasEtal%20Pigmy%20Falcon%20Ostrich04.pdf|archive-date= 2011-07-18}}</ref>

Reptile species also use the nests. Snakes, especially [[Cape cobra]]s and [[boomslang]]s, are the most common nest predators, often consuming all the eggs in all the chambers of a large nest.<ref name="bartholomew" /> Nest predation is often as high; in one study, 70% of the clutches laid were preyed upon.<ref name="covas" /> In addition, ''[[Trachylepis spilogaster]]'' (Kalahari Tree Skink) associate with the nests. Trees with nests appear to host more skinks than trees without nests.<ref name="Rymer">{{cite journal|last1=Rymer|first1=Tasmin L|last2=Thomson|first2=Robert L|last3=Whiting|first3=Martin J|title=At home with the birds: Kalahari tree skinks associate with sociable weaver nests despite African pygmy falcon presence|journal=Austral Ecology|date=Nov 2014|volume=39|issue=7|pages=839–847|url= https://repository.up.ac.za/dspace/bitstream/handle/2263/43816/Rymer_At_2014.pdf;sequence=1 |doi=10.1111/aec.12152|bibcode=2014AusEc..39..839R |hdl=2263/43816|hdl-access=free}}</ref> Additionally, these skinks have learned to eavesdrop on sociable weaver alarm calls to determine when a pygmy falcon, one of its main predators, is approaching.<ref name = "Lowney">{{cite journal|last1=Lowney|first1=Anthony M|last2=Flower|first2=Tom P|last3=Thomson|first3=Robert L|title=Kalahari skinks eavesdrop on sociable weavers to manage predation by pygmy falcons and expand their realized niche presence|journal=Behavioral Ecology|date=Jun 2020|volume=31|issue=5|pages=1094–1102|doi=10.1093/beheco/araa057|doi-access=free}}</ref>

Nests built in electricity poles sometimes cause short circuits in the rainy season and can catch fire in the dry season.<ref name=":0">[http://www.nnf.org.na/NNF_docs/NamPower-NNF%20training%20workshop%20report%20-%20Tsumeb%20&%20Otjiwarongo%20(23%20&%2024%20Sep%2009).pdf Management of Wildlife interactions with power line networks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720185732/http://www.nnf.org.na/NNF_docs/NamPower-NNF%20training%20workshop%20report%20-%20Tsumeb%20%26%20Otjiwarongo%20%2823%20%26%2024%20Sep%2009%29.pdf |date=2011-07-20 }}. NamPower/NNF Strategic Partnership (2009).</ref>

Some evidence indicates that cooperation in nest-building is driven by [[kin selection]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1= van Dijk|first1= René E.|last2= Kaden|first2= Jennifer C.|last3= Argüelles-Ticó|first3= Araceli|last4= Dawson|first4= Deborah A.|last5= Burke|first5= Terry|last6= Hatchwell|first6= Ben J.|last7= Westneat|first7= David|year= 2014|title= Cooperative investment in public goods is kin directed in communal nests of social birds|journal= Ecology Letters|volume= 17|issue= 9|pages= 1141–1148|doi= 10.1111/ele.12320|pmid= 25039999|pmc= 4282064|bibcode= 2014EcolL..17.1141V}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton|first1= Gavin M.|last2= Echeverri|first2= Sebastian|last3= Heinrich|first3= Dirk|last4= Kolberg|first4= Holger|date= 2015-08-29|title= Relatedness predicts multiple measures of investment in cooperative nest construction in sociable weavers|journal= Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|language= en|volume= 69|issue= 11|pages= 1835–1843|doi= 10.1007/s00265-015-1996-8|issn= 0340-5443|pmc= 4693614|pmid= 26726282|bibcode= 2015BEcoS..69.1835L}}</ref>

The bird droppings under the nesting colonies of the sociable weaver are used by [[Scarabaeinae|scarab]] beetles.<ref>{{cite web|title=A tree with the nesting colonies of the sociable weaver grows along D707 road in Namibia|url=https://independent-travellers.com/namibia/d707/index.php#bird|website=Independent Travellers|publisher=independent-travellers.com|access-date=December 24, 2017}}</ref>

=== Diet ===
The sociable weaver is insectivorous, with insects comprising 80% of their diet. As an adaptation to living in the dry Kalahari Desert, where standing water is scarce, the sociable weaver obtains all of its water from its diet. It also feeds on seeds and other plant products. [[Foraging]] is predominantly on the ground, but also on bark and leaves of trees.<ref name=covas />

== Status ==
Populations of the sociable weavers increased during the 2010s, perhaps due to increased availability of nesting structures such as electricity pylons and other man-made structures.<ref name=":0" /> Most of its present distribution is unlikely to see any major man-made alteration and its future in these areas is secure. A gap seen in its distribution in the Northern Cape Province, north of the [[Ghaap Plateau]] is probably due to habitat alteration by clearance of ''[[Acacia sensu lato|Acacia]]''. In other areas, encroachment due to overgrazing may also cause [[local extinction]].<ref name="mendelsohn" />

